### Describe the bug

Run this application on .NET 11 Windows and Linux. Navigate to the `/html` page and click `Send POST` button.
The result is different on Windows and Linux.

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
var app = builder.Build();
app.MapGet("/hello", () =>
{
    return TypedResults.Ok("hello");
});
app.MapPost("/posthiddenfield", ([FromForm] string field) =>
{
    return TypedResults.LocalRedirect("/hello");
});
app.MapGet("/html", async (HttpContext ctx) =>
{
    await ctx.Response.WriteAsync($$"""
            <!DOCTYPE html>
            <html>
            <body>
            <form action="/posthiddenfield" method="post">
                <input type="hidden" name="field" value="value">
                <button type="submit">Send POST</button>
            </form>
            </body>
            </html>
            """);
});
app.Run();
```

### Expected Behavior

When the application is hosted on Linux (WSL) and the app is opened on Windows (Chrome and Firefox):

```
InvalidOperationException: Endpoint HTTP: POST /posthiddenfield contains anti-forgery metadata, but a middleware was not found that supports anti-forgery.
Configure your application startup by adding app.UseAntiforgery() in the application startup code. If there are calls to app.UseRouting() and app.UseEndpoints(...), the call to app.UseAntiforgery() must go between them. Calls to app.UseAntiforgery() must be placed after calls to app.UseAuthentication() and app.UseAuthorization().
```

When the application is hosted on Windows "hello" is displayed after the redirects (same Windows client with Chrome and Firefox)

### Steps To Reproduce

See the steps described above.

### Exceptions (if any)

_No response_

### .NET Version

.NET 11 Preview 6

### Anything else?

On .NET 10 they seem to work in an identical way.

## Summary
Add support for selecting certificate store certificates by thumbprint in Kestrel configuration.

## Motivation and goals
Currently, Kestrel can only load certificates from the certificate store by subject name using `CertificateLoader.LoadFromStoreCert()`. A subject name is not guaranteed to uniquely identify a certificate, and modern certificates frequently rely on Subject Alternative Names (SANs), with the Common Name (CN) sometimes left empty. As a result, Kestrel configuration cannot always select the intended certificate from the certificate store.

Adding the ability to specify a certificate's thumbprint addresses this limitation. The .NET runtime already exposes `X509FindType.FindByThumbprint`, making the implementation of this proposal a relatively small change.

## In scope
- Adding the `Thumbprint` property to `Kestrel.Core.Internal.CertificateConfig`.
- Extending `CertificateLoader.LoadFromStoreCert()` to support thumbprint lookup.

## Out of scope
- Adding support for other lookup criteria such as Subject Alternative Name(s), Subject Distinguished Name, Issuer Distinguished Name or other certificate attributes.
	- SAN-based lookup could address some scenarios, but it introduces ambiguity when multiple certificates contain the same SAN entry and would require substantially broader changes. Thumbprint lookup provides deterministic certificate selection while keeping this proposal narrowly scoped.

## Risks / unknowns
- By specifying neither `Subject` nor `Thumbprint`.
- By specifying both `Subject` and `Thumbprint`, which necessitates an order of precedence. Should this behavior be allowed at all?
- By specifying thumbprints containing separators such as whitespace or colons. Should thumbprints be normalized?

## Examples
- In code using the proposed API: `var cert = LoadFromStoreCert(null, "8DDCFD0A1DA98A48B1A8A882CF68C5DC94A02C5A", "My", StoreLocation.LocalMachine, false);`
- In an `appsettings.json` configuration:
```json
{
  "Kestrel": {
    "Endpoints": {
      "Http": {
        "Url": "http://localhost:8080"
      },
      "Https": {
        "Url": "https://localhost:8443",
        "Certificate": {
          "Thumbprint": "8DDCFD0A1DA98A48B1A8A882CF68C5DC94A02C5A",
          "Store": "My",
          "Location": "LocalMachine"
		}
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Applies the approved API review decisions for the Blazor `BrowserOptions` surface that flows host configuration to the browser client via the `<!--Blazor-Configuration:{...}-->` DOM comment. The wire format is preserved through JSON converters/attributes, so no JS changes are required.

## Description

- **Render-mode property renames** on `BrowserOptions` (get-only, pre-initialized), with `[JsonPropertyName]` keeping the existing wire keys:
  - `Server` ŌåÆ `InteractiveServer` (`server`)
  - `Ssr` ŌåÆ `StaticServer` (`ssr`)
  - `WebAssembly` ŌåÆ `InteractiveWebAssembly` (`webAssembly`)
- **Type renames:** `SsrBrowserOptions` ŌåÆ `StaticServerBrowserOptions`, `WebAssemblyBrowserOptions` ŌåÆ `InteractiveWebAssemblyBrowserOptions` (`InteractiveServerBrowserOptions` unchanged).
- **Accessor moved off `HttpContext`:** removed `BrowserOptionsHttpContextExtensions`; `GetBrowserOptions` is now a static method `BrowserOptions.GetBrowserOptions(HttpContext)`.
- **`ConfigureBrowser`:** the `HttpContext` cascading parameter is now `internal`, removing it from the public API while remaining functional.
- Updated internal consumers (`EndpointHtmlRenderer`, `Server.AutoPause`, test server startup, `Root.razor`) and `PublicAPI.Unshipped.txt`.
- Added `BrowserOptionsTest` covering wire-key preservation, `TimeSpan`ŌåÆms conversion, negated `PreserveDom`ŌåÆ`disableDomPreservation`, extension-data flattening, `GetBrowserOptions` caching/metadata seeding, and `MergeInto` semantics.

```csharp
app.MapRazorComponents<App>()
    .WithBrowserOptions(options =>
    {
        options.LogLevel = LogLevel.Warning;
        options.InteractiveServer.ReconnectionMaxRetries = 10;
        options.InteractiveServer.ReconnectionRetryInterval = TimeSpan.FromSeconds(1.5);
        options.StaticServer.PreserveDom = true;
        options.InteractiveWebAssembly.EnvironmentName = "Staging";
        options.InteractiveWebAssembly.EnvironmentVariables["OTEL_ENDPOINT"] = "https://...";
    });
```

## Summary

Adds two public, non-experimental APIs to `QuickGrid<TGridItem>` that forward to its inner `Virtualize` component:

- **`InitialItemIndex`** parameter - scrolls to the given row on first interactive render (clamped, applied once).
- **`ScrollToItemAsync(int itemIndex, CancellationToken)`** method - programmatically scrolls to a row, aligning it to the top. Last call wins; throws `InvalidOperationException` when `Virtualize` is disabled or the grid isn't rendered yet.

These mirror the existing `Virtualize.InitialItemIndex` / `Virtualize.ScrollToItemAsync` APIs from https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/issues/66328.

### API surface

```csharp
namespace Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.QuickGrid;

public partial class QuickGrid<TGridItem> : ComponentBase
{
    // Applies only when Virtualize is true.
    [Parameter]
    public int InitialItemIndex { get; set; }

    public Task ScrollToItemAsync(int itemIndex, CancellationToken cancellationToken = default);
}
```

### Usage example
```razor
<QuickGrid @ref="_grid" Items="@people" Virtualize="true" ItemSize="50" InitialItemIndex="500">
    <PropertyColumn Property="@(p => p.Name)" />
    <PropertyColumn Property="@(p => p.Age)" />
</QuickGrid>

<button @onclick="() => _grid.ScrollToItemAsync(500)">Jump to 500</button>

@code {
    QuickGrid<Person> _grid = default!;
}
```

The dev-time Blazor Gateway runs with its content root set to the package's tools folder, so it never reads the WASM app project's `appsettings.json` / `appsettings.Development.json`. YARP `ReverseProxy` config could only be supplied via flattened `ReverseProxy__...` environment variables or command-line args ŌĆö verbose, error-prone, and undiscoverable. This lets the gateway pick up the standard `ReverseProxy` section straight from the app project's config files.

## Description

- **`BlazorGateway.BuildWebHost`**: new `AddAppProjectConfiguration` step reads an `AppSettingsDirectory` key and registers `appsettings.json` + `appsettings.{Environment}.json` from that directory via a `PhysicalFileProvider` (needed since the gateway's content root differs from the app project).
- **Source precedence**: the file sources are inserted just ahead of the environment-variable and command-line sources, preserving `command-line > env vars > appsettings.{Environment}.json > appsettings.json`. The existing env-var/`launchSettings.json` approach keeps working.
- **`Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.Gateway.targets`**: run arguments now pass `--AppSettingsDirectory "$(MSBuildProjectDirectory)"` so the gateway knows where the app project lives (VS F5, `dotnet run`, etc.).
- **Tests**: added coverage for config-file-based `ReverseProxy` forwarding and for `appsettings.{Environment}.json` overriding the base file.

Users can now configure the proxy with the standard, IntelliSense-friendly section:

```json
{
  "ReverseProxy": {
    "Routes": {
      "weather": { "ClusterId": "backend", "Match": { "Path": "/api/{**catch-all}" } }
    },
    "Clusters": {
      "backend": { "Destinations": { "backend1": { "Address": "http://localhost:5100/" } } }
    }
  }
}
```

 **_This proposal was prototyped before - look at https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/pull/67912_**

> **Status: experimental, Linux-only.** Every public type and member below is gated behind the `[Experimental("ASPNETCORE_DIRECTTLS_001")]` diagnostic (`UrlFormat = https://aka.ms/aspnetcore/directtls`). Consumers opt in with `#pragma warning disable ASPNETCORE_DIRECTTLS_001` (or `<NoWarn>`).

---

## 0. Background

TLS termination in Kestrel today goes through `SslStream`, which copies application bytes through managed BIO buffers on top of the socket. The goal of DirectTls is to make TLS-bound traffic perform better by terminating TLS directly on the socket's file descriptor. It does this with the runtime's low-level, fd-bound OpenSSL TLS session (`System.Net.Security.TlsContext` / `TlsSocketSession` from https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/issues/128871), so encrypted bytes are read from and written to the socket fd without the extra `SslStream` buffering layer. The transport is a drop-in alternative for a Kestrel HTTPS endpoint ŌĆö same certificates, SNI, ALPN, and mTLS knobs ŌĆö that you opt into per endpoint.

---

## 1. Why a separate assembly

DirectTls ships as its own assembly, **`Microsoft.AspNetCore.Server.Kestrel.Transport.DirectTls`**, rather than being folded into `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Server.Kestrel.Transport.Sockets` or Kestrel core. Like the other Kestrel transports, the assembly is part of the ASP.NET Core shared framework (`<IsAspNetCoreApp>true</IsAspNetCoreApp>`), so it is *present* on any ASP.NET Core host ŌĆö it is not a separate NuGet package you acquire. The separation is about layering, isolation, and trimmability, not distribution:

- **Layering ŌĆö it references Kestrel core directly.** Unlike the general-purpose Sockets/Quic transports (which only know about raw bytes), DirectTls terminates TLS and is tightly integrated with Kestrel's HTTPS semantics: it reads `HttpProtocols` (ALPN), `ClientCertificateMode`, and publishes `ITlsApplicationProtocolFeature` ŌĆö all of which live in `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Server.Kestrel.Core`. Putting it in its own assembly lets it take that `Kestrel.Core` reference **without** dragging TLS/OpenSSL concerns into the default socket transport, which stays a plaintext, protocol-agnostic byte pipe. The dependency direction is one-way (`Transport.DirectTls` ŌåÆ `Kestrel.Core`); core never references the transport, so there is no cycle.

- **Dependency isolation.** The transport consumes an experimental runtime API (`TlsContext` / `TlsSocketSession`, gated behind `SYSLIB5007`) and requires OpenSSL (`libssl`) at runtime. Isolating that in its own assembly keeps the experimental surface ŌĆö and its `NoWarn` (`SYSLIB5007`, `ASPNETCORE_DIRECTTLS_001`) ŌĆö out of the shipped Kestrel transport assemblies.

- **Trimmable / opt-in.** The transport is only wired up when you call `UseDirectTlsTransport()`. The assembly is marked `<IsTrimmable>true</IsTrimmable>`, so for trimmed or Native AOT apps that never call it, the linker can remove it entirely ŌĆö you don't pay for it if you don't use it. Registration is additive: `UseDirectTlsTransport()` adds the transport next to the default one and only claims `DirectTlsEndpoint` endpoints; every other endpoint keeps using the default transport.

- **Experimental gate.** The `[Experimental("ASPNETCORE_DIRECTTLS_001")]` attribute is the real opt-in: you must explicitly suppress the diagnostic to use the API, which keeps it clearly separate from stable Kestrel surface while it is being validated.

---

## 2. API surface

Two namespaces are involved:

- `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Hosting` ŌĆö the registration extension methods.
- `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Server.Kestrel.Transport.DirectTls` ŌĆö the endpoint and options types.

### 2.1 Registration ŌĆö `WebHostBuilderDirectTlsExtensions`

```csharp
namespace Microsoft.AspNetCore.Hosting;

[Experimental("ASPNETCORE_DIRECTTLS_001", UrlFormat = "https://aka.ms/aspnetcore/directtls")]
public static class WebHostBuilderDirectTlsExtensions
{
    // Register the transport with defaults.
    public static IWebHostBuilder UseDirectTlsTransport(this IWebHostBuilder hostBuilder);

    // Register the transport and configure transport-wide options.
    public static IWebHostBuilder UseDirectTlsTransport(
        this IWebHostBuilder hostBuilder,
        Action<DirectTlsTransportOptions> configureOptions);
}
```

Call this **after** `UseKestrel()`. The DirectTls factory is registered additively (last-registered is tried first), and its `CanBind` claims only `DirectTlsEndpoint`; all other endpoint types fall through to the default transport.

### 2.2 Transport-wide options ŌĆö `DirectTlsTransportOptions`

```csharp
namespace Microsoft.AspNetCore.Server.Kestrel.Transport.DirectTls;

[Experimental("ASPNETCORE_DIRECTTLS_001", UrlFormat = "https://aka.ms/aspnetcore/directtls")]
public sealed class DirectTlsTransportOptions
{
    // Number of epoll event-pump threads the transport spreads accepted connections across. Default: 4.
    public int WorkerCount { get; set; } = 4;
}
```

### 2.3 The endpoint ŌĆö `DirectTlsEndpoint`

An `IPEndPoint` subtype that opts a single Kestrel listener into the DirectTls transport. Bind it with `KestrelServerOptions.Listen(...)` (or `ListenAnyIP` / `ListenLocalhost`).

```csharp
namespace Microsoft.AspNetCore.Server.Kestrel.Transport.DirectTls;

[Experimental("ASPNETCORE_DIRECTTLS_001", UrlFormat = "https://aka.ms/aspnetcore/directtls")]
public sealed class DirectTlsEndpoint : IPEndPoint
{
    public DirectTlsEndpoint(IPAddress address, int port);
    public DirectTlsEndpoint(IPAddress address, int port, DirectTlsEndpointOptions options);
    public DirectTlsEndpoint(int port, DirectTlsEndpointOptions options);            // listens on IPAddress.Any
    public DirectTlsEndpoint(IPEndPoint endpoint, DirectTlsEndpointOptions options);

    // Per-endpoint TLS configuration. Never null (a default instance is created by the first ctor).
    public DirectTlsEndpointOptions Options { get; }
}
```

### 2.4 Per-endpoint TLS configuration ŌĆö `DirectTlsEndpointOptions`

DirectTls is **TLS-only**: every endpoint terminates TLS, so a server certificate is required (either `ServerCertificate` or `ServerCertificateSelector`). The members mirror `HttpsConnectionAdapterOptions` so an existing HTTPS endpoint maps over with the same knobs.

```csharp
namespace Microsoft.AspNetCore.Server.Kestrel.Transport.DirectTls;

[Experimental("ASPNETCORE_DIRECTTLS_001", UrlFormat = "https://aka.ms/aspnetcore/directtls")]
public sealed class DirectTlsEndpointOptions
{
    // The certificate presented during the handshake (used when the selector is unset or returns null).
    public X509Certificate2? ServerCertificate { get; set; }

    // Selects the certificate from the connection + SNI host parsed from the ClientHello. Returning null falls back to ServerCertificate.
    public Func<ConnectionContext?, string?, X509Certificate2?>? ServerCertificateSelector { get; set; }

    // Protocols offered on this endpoint; drives the ALPN list (h2 is offered when Http2 is included). Default: HttpProtocols.Http1AndHttp2.
    public HttpProtocols HttpProtocols { get; set; }

    // Allowable TLS versions. Default: SslProtocols.None (OS default).
    public SslProtocols SslProtocols { get; set; }

    // Whether a client certificate is requested/required (mTLS). Default: ClientCertificateMode.NoCertificate. ClientCertificateMode.DelayCertificate is not supported.
    public ClientCertificateMode ClientCertificateMode { get; set; }

    // Validates a client certificate when one is requested. Return true to accept. When unset, a certificate is accepted only when it produced no SslPolicyErrors.
    public Func<X509Certificate2, X509Chain?, SslPolicyErrors, bool>? ClientCertificateValidation { get; set; }

    // Observes the raw ClientHello record bytes as soon as they are parsed (fingerprinting/telemetry). Observation only ŌĆö it cannot alter or reject the handshake.
    public Action<ConnectionContext, ReadOnlySequence<byte>>? TlsClientHelloBytesCallback { get; set; }
}
```

| Member | Type | Default | Equivalent in today's API | Purpose |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| `ServerCertificate` | `X509Certificate2?` | `null` | `HttpsConnectionAdapterOptions.ServerCertificate` | Static server certificate. |
| `ServerCertificateSelector` | `Func<ConnectionContext?, string?, X509Certificate2?>?` | `null` | `HttpsConnectionAdapterOptions.ServerCertificateSelector` (identical signature) | Per-connection SNI certificate selection. |
| `HttpProtocols` | `HttpProtocols` | `Http1AndHttp2` | `ListenOptions.Protocols` | ALPN advertisement (h2 negotiation). |
| `SslProtocols` | `SslProtocols` | `None` | `HttpsConnectionAdapterOptions.SslProtocols` | Allowable TLS versions. |
| `ClientCertificateMode` | `ClientCertificateMode` | `NoCertificate` | `HttpsConnectionAdapterOptions.ClientCertificateMode` | mTLS request/require (no `DelayCertificate`). |
| `ClientCertificateValidation` | `Func<X509Certificate2, X509Chain?, SslPolicyErrors, bool>?` | `null` | `HttpsConnectionAdapterOptions.ClientCertificateValidation` (identical signature) | Client certificate acceptance. |
| `TlsClientHelloBytesCallback` | `Action<ConnectionContext, ReadOnlySequence<byte>>?` | `null` | `HttpsConnectionAdapterOptions.TlsClientHelloBytesCallback` (identical signature) | Raw ClientHello observation. |

---

## 3. Usage from `Program.cs`

### 3.1 Minimal ŌĆö one HTTPS endpoint

```csharp
using System.Net;
using System.Security.Cryptography.X509Certificates;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Server.Kestrel.Transport.DirectTls;

#pragma warning disable ASPNETCORE_DIRECTTLS_001

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Register the DirectTls transport AFTER UseKestrel.
builder.WebHost.UseKestrel();
builder.WebHost.UseDirectTlsTransport();

builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(options =>
{
    var endpoint = new DirectTlsEndpoint(IPAddress.Any, 5001);
    endpoint.Options.ServerCertificate =
        X509Certificate2.CreateFromPemFile("server.crt", "server.key");
    options.Listen(endpoint);
});

var app = builder.Build();
app.MapGet("/", (HttpContext ctx) => $"Hello over {ctx.Request.Protocol}");
app.Run();
```

### 3.2 Full-featured endpoint ŌĆö SNI selection, ALPN/HTTP-2, ClientHello observation

```csharp
var p256 = X509Certificate2.CreateFromPemFile("server-p256.crt", "server-p256.key");
var p384 = X509Certificate2.CreateFromPemFile("server-p384.crt", "server-p384.key");

builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(options =>
{
    var endpoint = new DirectTlsEndpoint(IPAddress.Any, 5001);

    // ALPN: offer h2 and http/1.1.
    endpoint.Options.HttpProtocols = HttpProtocols.Http1AndHttp2;

    // Per-connection certificate selection by ClientHello SNI host.
    endpoint.Options.ServerCertificateSelector = (connection, host) =>
        string.Equals(host, "p384.example", StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase) ? p384 : p256;

    // Observe the raw ClientHello (bytes[0] == 0x16 handshake record). Observation only.
    endpoint.Options.TlsClientHelloBytesCallback = (connection, clientHelloBytes) =>
        Console.WriteLine($"[ClientHello] {connection.ConnectionId}: {clientHelloBytes.Length} bytes");

    options.Listen(endpoint);
});
```

### 3.3 Mutual TLS (client certificates)

```csharp
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(options =>
{
    // Bind on IPAddress.Any via the (int port, options) convenience ctor.
    var endpoint = new DirectTlsEndpoint(5001, new DirectTlsEndpointOptions
    {
        ServerCertificate = serverCertificate,
        ClientCertificateMode = ClientCertificateMode.RequireCertificate,
        ClientCertificateValidation = (clientCert, chain, errors) => errors == SslPolicyErrors.None,
    });
    options.Listen(endpoint);
});
```

### 3.4 Tuning the transport (event-pump threads)

```csharp
builder.WebHost.UseKestrel();
builder.WebHost.UseDirectTlsTransport(transport =>
{
    transport.WorkerCount = 8; // number of epoll pump threads
});
```

> **Note:** Only endpoints bound as a `DirectTlsEndpoint` use this transport. Any regular `IPEndPoint` (or `UseHttps` endpoint) continues to use the default Kestrel transport, so DirectTls and the default transport can coexist in the same host.

